<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12031b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12031b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12031b"> 31(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cocks lay eggs</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">137 (<i>Le myst&egrave;re de l&apos;aigle &agrave; l&apos;oeuf d&apos;or</i>): Faut-il aussi remarquer que l&apos;auteur de la brochure de 1622 met toujours an masculin l&apos;oiseau qui pond l&apos;&oelig;uf: c&apos;est le bouleversement de l&apos;histoire naturelle! Je me rappelle, toutefois, avoir entendu dire qu&apos;au Mont-Saint-Michel et sur la c&ocirc;te voisine, les coqs pondaient des &oelig;ufs. Je demandai, un jour, &agrave; un grand savant, l&apos;explication de ce ph&eacute;nom&egrave;ne: &ldquo;Oubliez- vous donc, me dit-il, qu&apos;au cours de la Guerre de Cent Ans, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire &agrave; l&apos;origine de l&apos;artillerie, le canon gronda terriblement au Mont-Saint-Michel? Tous les coqs du pays furent &eacute;pouvant&eacute;s: <i>ils eurent la chair de poule</i>.&rdquo;] ? Vraiment, les folkloristes ont r&eacute;ponse &agrave; tout. <br><font color="green">[Must we add that the author of the 1622 brochure always makes the bird that lays the egg masculine: it overturns the natural order! I remember, in any case, being told that in Mont-Saint-Michel and the neighbouring coast, the roosters laid the eggs. I asked a very clever man for an explanation: &ldquo;Have you forgotten, he said, that during the Hundred Year War, when artillery was first used, the canons blew terribly on Mont-Saint- Michel? All the roosters of the land were terrified: <i>they were all chicken</i>. It is true: folklore specialists have an answer for everything.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 137</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
